Worksheet 2 - Net migration barchart

  • Dataset
  • Final plot

This worksheet’s dataset is modified from one found at the World Bank.

↓ Click the link below to download the dataset for this worksheet to your hard drive.

migration.csv

1 Step-by-step

1.1 Read in data from csv

Instead of readxl::read_xlsx we’ll use the read_csv function from the readr package.

Show the code 
data_raw <- 
  readr::read_csv(file = "migration.csv")

1.2 Make a basic barchart

Use ggplot and a geom_col to make a bar chart. Then use aes to map the x and y axes to the year and net migration columns. Don’t forget the backticks around column names that have spaces in them!

Show the code 
data_raw |> 
  ggplot2::ggplot() + 
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year, 
                                           y = `Net migration`))

1.3 Add a theme

Add an out-of-the-box ggplot2 theme like theme_classic to make the plot look a bit nicer.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`)) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

1.4 Add a facet

Add a facet_wrap to make a small plot for every unique value in the country name column (I know they’re not really countries!). I’ve constrained it to only use one column with the ‘ncol’ argument.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`)) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`), 
                      ncol = 1) + 
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

1.5 Fix the x axis breaks

Add a scale_x_continuous and modify the ‘breaks’ argument to force them to be a different width.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`)) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) + 
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

1.6 Fix the y axis labels

Add a scale_y_continuous and modify the ‘labels’ argument change e.g. 2e+06 (equal to 2 million) to 2M.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`)) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6, 
                                                           suffix = "M")) + 
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

1.7 Fill the bars depending on +/-

Add a ‘fill’ argument to aes and set it to ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0). This fill the bars differently depending on whether they are above or below zero on the y axis.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) + 
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

1.8 Customise the palette

Customise the palette for your new fill aesthetic by adding a scale_fill_manual and specifying the ‘values’ argument. The fill aesthetic created by the after_stat function has the values TRUE or FALSE depending on whether it’s above or below zero on the y axis.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M")) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) + 
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic()

1.9 Remove the legend

Add a theme function, after your out-of-the-box theme, and specify the ‘legend.position’ argument as “none”.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M")) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

1.10 Add some horizontal lines

Add three geom_hline functions (hline means horizontal line) before the geom_col. Specify the ‘yintercept’ argument for each so that we get lines at -2M, 0, and +2M.

I’ve also specified the ‘colour’ for each as ‘lightgrey’, the ‘linetype’ as “longdash” for two, and the ‘alpha’ (transparency) as either 0.5 or 0.75.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0, 
                      colour = "lightgrey", 
                      alpha = 0.75) + 
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 2*10^6, 
                      colour = "lightgrey", 
                      linetype = "longdash", 
                      alpha = 0.5) + 
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = -2*10^6, 
                      colour = "lightgrey", 
                      linetype = "longdash", 
                      alpha = 0.5) + 
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M")) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

1.11 Add a vertical line

Add a geom_vline function (vline means vertical line) before the geom_col. Specify the ‘xintercept’ argument as 2023 or 202. The data to the right are in the future!

I’ve also specified the ‘colour’, ‘linetype’, and ‘alpha’ arguments, just like for the horizontal lines.

Show the code 
data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = -2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = 2024, 
                      colour = "grey", 
                      linetype = "dashed", 
                      alpha = 0.75) + 
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M")) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

1.12 Fix y axis range

We want to set the y axis so there is an equal distance (e.g. 2.5M) above zero as there is below - making it more symmetrical, and perhaps easier to see the overall pattern.

First, before the plot statement, make another statement to create an object which will contain the maximum absolute value of the y axis.

Absolute means you are not interested in the negative or positive sign of each number. So for these numbers (-1000, 0, 900), the maximum absolute value would be 1000.

Use the max and abs functions to find the maximum absolute value in the net migration column and save it into your new object. Don’t forget to set the ‘na.rm’ argument of max to TRUE in case there are NA values.

Then use this new object to set the ‘limits’ argument of the scale_y_continuous function you made earlier.

Show the code 
max_y_axis <- 
  max(abs(data_raw$`Net migration`), na.rm = TRUE) 

data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = -2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = 2024,
                      colour = "grey",
                      linetype = "dashed",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M"),
                              limits = c(-max_y_axis, max_y_axis)) + 
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

1.13 Change column border colours

Sometimes columns can look a bit funny with a white border. We’ve changed the fill, but let’s change the border colour as well.

Replicate everything you did to change the fill aesthetic and change the colour aesthetic as well. You’ll need to make changes inside aes and you’ll need to add a scale_colour_manual to replicate the scale_fill_manual.

Show the code 
max_y_axis <-
  max(abs(data_raw$`Net migration`), na.rm = TRUE)

data_raw |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = -2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = 2024,
                      colour = "grey",
                      linetype = "dashed",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0),
                                           colour = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) + 
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M"),
                              limits = c(-max_y_axis, max_y_axis)) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::scale_colour_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) + 
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

1.14 Reorder your facets

To rearrange the facets in order of total net migration we need to use a mutate function from the dplyr package. This can modify the country name column (because that’s the one used to facet the plot) in the data before passing it to the plot. We can add this mutate on the line right before the first ggplot function.

Use the fct_reorder function from the forcats package (an anagram of factors!) inside the mutate function. You’ll need to specify several arguments for fct_reorder including ‘.f’, ‘.x’, ‘.fun’, and ‘.desc’ to get it looking just like the one below.

Now we have the area with the most positive all-time total net migration at the top, and the one with the most negative at the bottom.

Show the code 
max_y_axis <-
  max(abs(data_raw$`Net migration`), na.rm = TRUE)

data_raw |>
  dplyr::mutate(`Country Name` = forcats::fct_reorder(`Country Name`, 
                                                      `Net migration`, 
                                                      .fun = sum, 
                                                      .desc = TRUE)) |> 
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = -2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = 2024,
                      colour = "grey",
                      linetype = "dashed",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0),
                                           colour = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M"),
                              limits = c(-max_y_axis, max_y_axis)) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::scale_colour_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

1.15 Save your plot

When you’re happy with your plot in the preview pane, save it into an object with <- and use the ggsave function to save it to a file. Try saving it into a folder called “plots”. You’ll have to make the folder first inside your RStudio project.

Show the code 
my_plot <- 
  data_raw |>
  dplyr::mutate(`Country Name` = forcats::fct_reorder(`Country Name`,
                                                      `Net migration`,
                                                      .fun = sum,
                                                      .desc = TRUE)) |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = -2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = 2024,
                      colour = "grey",
                      linetype = "dashed",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0),
                                           colour = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M"),
                              limits = c(-max_y_axis, max_y_axis)) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::scale_colour_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")

ggplot2::ggsave(filename = "plots/plot_01.png", 
                plot = my_plot, 
                width = 150, 
                height = 300, 
                units = "mm", 
                dpi = 300)

2 The final script

# READ IN DATA FROM EXCEL FILE --------------------------------------------

data_raw <-
  readr::read_csv(file = "migration.csv")


# MAKE PLOT ---------------------------------------------------------------

max_y_axis <-
  max(abs(data_raw$`Net migration`), na.rm = TRUE)

my_plot <-
  data_raw |>
  dplyr::mutate(`Country Name` = forcats::fct_reorder(`Country Name`,
                                                      `Net migration`,
                                                      .fun = sum,
                                                      .desc = TRUE)) |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = 2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_hline(yintercept = -2*10^6,
                      colour = "lightgrey",
                      linetype = "longdash",
                      alpha = 0.5) +
  ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = 2024,
                      colour = "grey",
                      linetype = "dashed",
                      alpha = 0.75) +
  ggplot2::geom_col(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year,
                                           y = `Net migration`,
                                           fill = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0),
                                           colour = ggplot2::after_stat(y > 0))) +
  ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(10)) +
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma(scale = 1*10^-6,
                                                           suffix = "M"),
                              limits = c(-max_y_axis, max_y_axis)) +
  ggplot2::scale_fill_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::scale_colour_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#194375", "FALSE" = "#FD700E")) +
  ggplot2::facet_wrap(facets = ggplot2::vars(`Country Name`),
                      ncol = 1) +
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")


# SAVE PLOT ---------------------------------------------------------------

ggplot2::ggsave(filename = "plots/plot_01.png",
                plot = my_plot,
                width = 150,
                height = 300,
                units = "mm",
                dpi = 300)
